item.label: Arteries
item.name: Arteries
item.description: The arterial supply to the brain is via the paired internal carotid and vertebral arteries. The terminal branches of the internal carotid arteries are the paired anterior and middle cerebral arteries which supply supratentorial structures.  The two vertebral arteries enter the cranial cavity via the foramen magnum; they join one another at the junction of the medulla with the pons to form the basilar artery.  Together the vertebral-basilar system of arteries supplies the structures of the posterior fossa as well as those supratentorial structures supplied by its terminal branches -- the posterior cerebral arteries.

item.label: Vertebral
item.name: Vertebral artery
item.description: Along with the internal carotid arteries, the vertebral arteries are the major blood supply to the brain. The two vertebral arteries fuse at the junction of the medulla and pons to form the basilar artery. The vertebral-basilar system supplies structures in the posterior fossa plus posterior aspects of the diencephalon, choroid plexus in the third and lateral ventricles and the medial and inferior surfaces of the occipital and temporal lobes of the cerebral hemispheres.

item.label: Anterior spinal
item.name: Anterior spinal artery
item.description: The anterior spinal artery originates as a branch from each of the vertebral arteries at the level of the medulla; these branches then join to form a single vessel which travels caudally in the ventral median fissure of the spinal cord. Along with tributaries from the radicular arteries, it supplies the anterior 2/3rds of the spinal cord.

item.label: Posterior inferior cerebellar
item.name: Posterior inferior cerebellar artery
item.description: The posterior inferior cerebellar artery is AKA the PICA.  It is a branch from the vertebral artery near its junction with the basilar artery. It supplies much of the inferior surface of the cerebellar hemispheres but very importantly, it supplies several functionally important structures on the dorsal lateral aspect of the medulla. Loss of this blood supply results in the PICA or lateral medullary syndrome.

item.label: Basilar
item.name: Basilar artery
item.description: The two vertebral arteries fuse at the junction of the medulla and pons to form the basilar artery. At the junction of the pons and midbrain, the basilar bifurcates into two terminal branches, the posterior cerebral arteries. Branches of the basilar & posterior cerebral arteries supply parts of the brain stem, cerebellum, posterior aspects of the diencephalon, choroid plexus in the third and lateral ventricles and the medial and inferior surfaces of the occipital and temporal lobes of the cerebral hemispheres.

item.label: Anterior inferior cerebellar
item.name: Anterior inferior cerebellar artery
item.description: The anterior inferior cerebellar artery [AICA] is a branch from the basilar artery just rostral to where the two vertebral arteries unite to form the basilar. It supplies the more anterior portions of the inferior surface of the cerebellum such as the flocculus plus parts of the caudal pons.

item.label: Pontine
item.name: Pontine arteries
item.description: The pontine arteries are multiple branches from the basilar artery on the ventral aspect of the pons.  They vascularize the pons via midline (paramedian) and lateral (short & long circumferential) branches.

item.label: Superior cerebellar
item.name: Superior cerebellar artery
item.description: The superior cerebellar artery is a branch from the basilar artery just caudal to the bifurcation of the basilar to form the two posterior cerebral arteries. It supplies the superior aspect of the cerebellum plus parts of the caudal midbrain and rostral pons.

item.label: Posterior cerebral
item.name: Posterior cerebral artery
item.description: The posterior cerebral arteries are paired vessels formed as the terminal branches of the basilar artery at the level of the midbrain. They are part of the posterior aspect of the circle of Willis and supply the rostral midbrain, posterior thalamus, medial occipital lobe as well as the inferior and medial surfaces of the temporal lobe. Disruption of the posterior cerebral artery may result in blindness in the contralateral visual field since it supplies the visual cortex of the occipital lobe; it may also present as a contralateral upper motor neuron lesion with spastic paralysis of the contralateral body and face as well as an ipsilateral lower motor neuron lesion of the oculomotor nerve/nucleus since it supplies the crus cerebri and oculumotor nerve/nucleus in the midbrain.

item.label: Cranial Nerves
item.name: Cranial Nerves
item.description: There are 12 pair of cranial nerves.  The Olfactory nerves (I) are associated with the telencephalon.  The Optic nerves (II) are associated with the diencephalon.  The Oculomotor (III) and Trochlear (IV) nerves are associated with the midbrain (mesencephalon).  The Trigeminal (V), Abducens (VI), Facial (VII) and Vestibulocochlear (VIII) are associated with the pons (metencephalon).  The Glossopharyngeal (IX), Vagus (X), Hypoglossal (XII) are associated with the medulla (myelencephalon).  The Accessory (XI) nerves originate in the cervical spinal cord.

item.label: Trochlear
item.name: Trochlear nerve
item.description: The fourth or trochlear cranial nerve innervates the superior oblique muscle of the contralateral eye. It is the only cranial nerve to exit the dorsal aspect of the brainstem. This location is just caudal to the inferior colliculi of the midbrain.

item.label: Trigeminal
item.name: Trigeminal nerve
item.description: The fifth or trigeminal cranial nerve enters/exits the brain stem through the basilar portion of the pons. It provides somatosensory innervation to the head via its ophthalmic, maxillary and mandibular roots which converge upon the trigeminal ganglion and then form a massive sensory root entering the brainstem. It provides motor innervation to the muscles derived from the first branchial arch (muscles of mastication, tensor tympani, anterior belly of diagastric, tensor veli palatini and mylohyoid) via a smaller motor root that distributes with the mandibular sensory root.

item.label: Abducens
item.name: Abducens nerve
item.description: The abducens nerve is the sixth cranial nerve.  It innervates the ipsilateral lateral rectus muscle. It exits the brain stem anteriorly at the pontomedullary junction.

item.label: Facial
item.name: Facial nerve
item.description: The facial or seventh cranial nerve has both sensory and motor components which enter/exit the brain stem in the cerebellopontine angle with the vestibulocochlear nerve. The most important sensory component carries taste from the anterior 2/3rds of the tongue; motor components innervate the skeletal muscles of facial expression, stapedius, etc. as well as provide the parasympathetic preganglionic fibers that control secretion of the submandibular, sublingual and lacrimal glands.

item.label: Vestibulocochlear
item.name: Vestibulocochlear nerve
item.description: The vestibulocochlear nerve is AKA the statoacoustic nerve. This eighth cranial nerve enters the brainstem at the cerebellopontine angle. It carries information from the hair cell receptors in the organ of Corti of the cochlear duct as well as from the vestibular organs (cristae of the semicircular ducts and maculae of the utricle and saccule of the inner ear).

item.label: Glossopharyngeal
item.name: Glossopharyngeal nerve
item.description: The ninth or glossopharyngeal cranial nerve has both sensory and motor components which enter/exit the brain stem along the lateral aspect of the medulla dorsal to the olive. The sensory component includes tactile sensation and taste from the posterior 1/3rd of the tongue as well as input from the carotid body/sinus, middle and external ear; the motor component innervates the stylopharyngeus muscle (3rd pharyngeal arch origin) and provides the parasympathetic preganglionic fibers that control secretion of the parotid gland.

item.label: Vagus
item.name: Vagus nerve
item.description: The tenth or vagus cranial nerve has both sensory and motor components which enter/exit the brain stem as a series of rootlets along the lateral aspect of the medulla dorsal to the olive and just caudal to the glossopharyngeal nerve. The most significant sensory component includes general sensation from the viscera, including input from the aortic body/sinus; the motor component innervates the laryngeal and pharyngeal muscles (4th and 6th pharyngeal arch origin) and provides the parasympathetic preganglionic fibers that innervate the thoracic and abdominal viscera.

item.label: Accessory
item.name: Accessory nerve
item.description: The accessory or eleventh cranial nerve originates from the (spinal) accessory nucleus located in the lateral aspect of the anterior horn of cervical spinal cord segments C1 to C5. The nerve roots emerge from the lateral aspect of the spinal cord, just dorsal to the denticulate ligament. The roots then turn rostrally, enter the cranium through the foramen magnum. The accessory nerve innervates the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles.

item.label: Hypoglossal
item.name: Hypoglossal nerve
item.description: The twelfth or hypoglossal cranial nerve is purely motor and innervates the ipsilateral intrinsic and extrinsic skeletal muscles of the tongue (except for the palatoglossus). It exits the medulla as a series of rootlets in the ventral lateral or anterolateral fissure between the olive and the pyramid in the medulla.

item.label: Cerebrum
item.name: Cerebrum
item.description: The cerebrum consists of the paired cerebral hemispheres.  Each cerebral hemisphere consists of lobes:  frontal, parietal, occipital, temporal.  In some instances a limbic lobe is designated-- consisting of a portion of the medial aspect of the other lobes.

item.label: Pons
item.name: Pons
item.description: The pons is that portion of the brainstem between the midbrain and medulla. It consists of a basilar or basal portion that contains structures primarily associated with motor control and a tegmental portion that contains cranial nerve nuclei and important sensory tracts. The cerebellum overlies the pons and medulla. The rostral aspect of the fourth ventricle is located on the dorsal surface of the pons. The pons and cerebellum originate embryologically from the metencephalon of the hindbrain.

item.label: Medulla
item.name: Medulla
item.description: The medulla is AKA the medulla oblongata. The most caudal aspect of the brain stem, it is located between the pons and spinal cord. It contains structures vital to survival such as cardiovascular and respiratory centers, as well as many cranial nerve nuclei. The major ascending and descending tracts travel through it between the spinal cord and higher centers. It originates developmentally from the myelencephalon of the hindbrain.

item.label: Cerebellum
item.name: Cerebellum
item.description: The cerebellum is sometimes referred to as the 'small' brain.  It is located within the posterior fossa, superior to the brain stem. It consists of a finely convoluted cortical surface of folia, a central core of white matter (AKA medullary center) and four paired deep nuclei (dentate, emboliform, fastigial and globose) embedded within the white matter core. The cerebellum functions in the planning and coordination of movement.

item.label: Spinal cord
item.name: Spinal cord
item.description: The spinal cord is that portion of the central nervous system that extends from the medulla to the conus medullaris. It consists of 31 segments (8 cervical, 12 thoracic, 5 lumbar, 5 sacral, 1 coccygeal) and has enlargements at the levels serving the limbs (C5 - T1 and L2 - S3).
